{"id":"2008.08689","submitter":"M. B. Paranjape","authors":"M. B. Paranjape","title":"You can see a clock running backwards in time","comments":"9 pages, 2 figures, 2020 Gravity Research Foundation Essay\n  Competition Honourable Mention","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1142/S0218271820430166","report-no":"UdeM-GPP-TH-20-282","categories":"gr-qc hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The epitome of acausal or anti-chronological behaviour would be to see a\nclock running backwards in time. In this essay we point out that this is indeed\npossible, but there is no problem with causality. What you see isn't what is\nreally happening. Locally, causality is always respected. However our\nobservation should be cause for pause to astronomers and cosmologists, who\nstrictly observe events occurring at very large distances or very long ago and\ncertainly not locally. It can be that what you see isn't what you necessarily\nget.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 19 Aug 2020 22:23:03 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-03"}
